03936nam a22006855i 9780813552064DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20112012nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135520647 a10.36019/97808135520642doi  a(DE-B1597)529228  a(OCoLC)778339829  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1995.9.H44bK56 2012 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.43/6522221 aKing, Claire Sisco, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWashed in Blood :bMale Sacrifice, Trauma, and the Cinema /cClaire Sisco King. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b24  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Reel Presence, Sacrifice, and the Cinema -- tChapter 2. Unhinged Heroes and Alpha Traumas -- tChapter 3. Free falls in the 1990s -- tChapter 4. Remakes, Resurrections, and Sacrificial Returns -- tEpilogue. Big-Screen Memories -- tNOTES -- tSELECTED BIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWill Smith in I Am Legend. Leonardo DiCaprio in Titanic. Charlton Heston in just about everything. Viewers of Hollywood action films are no doubt familiar with the sacrificial victim-hero, the male protagonist who nobly gives up his life so that others may be saved. Washed in Blood argues that such sacrificial films are especially prominent in eras when the nation—and American manhood—is thought to be in crisis. The sacrificial victim-hero, continually imperiled and frequently exhibiting classic symptoms of post-traumatic stress disorder, thus bears the trauma of the nation. Claire Sisco King offers an in-depth study of three prominent cycles of Hollywood films that follow the sacrificial narrative: the early–to–mid 1970s, the mid–to–late 1990s, and the mid–to–late 2000s. From Vietnam-era disaster movies to post-9/11 apocalyptic thrillers, she examines how each film represents traumatized American masculinity and national identity. What she uncovers is a cinematic tendency to position straight white men as America’s most valuable citizens—and its noblest victims.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aDeath in motion pictures. 0aHeroes in motion pictures. 0aPsychic trauma in motion pictures. 0aSacrifice in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355206440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813552064423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780813552064/original  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK